notes.body:
Pre-order, in-order and post-order are not three algorithms. They are **one recursion** that differs only in *when* you touch the current node relative to its two child calls:

```cpp
struct TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode *left, *right;
    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
};

// ---------- DFS traversals: order = WHEN you visit `node` ----------
void dfs(TreeNode* node, vector<int>& out) {
    if (!node) return;
    // out.push_back(node->val);   // PRE-order:  node, left, right
    dfs(node->left, out);
    // out.push_back(node->val);   // IN-order:   left, node, right  (BST -> sorted!)
    dfs(node->right, out);
    // out.push_back(node->val);   // POST-order: left, right, node  (children before parent)
}
```

[[fig:m06-traversal-orders]]

Each order has a *personality* — knowing which to grab is half the problem:

- **Pre-order** touches the node before its children → good when the parent decides something the children need (serialization, copying a tree, passing bounds down).
- **In-order** on a **BST** visits values in sorted order → "kth smallest", "validate", "find pair" all fall out of this one fact.
- **Post-order** touches the node after both children → the natural home of the packet pattern, because you can only combine children's answers *after* you have them.

> [!INTUITION]
> Ask yourself: "do I need my children's answers before I can act?" If yes, you're writing post-order whether you call it that or not. Height, balance, diameter, LCA — all post-order at heart.

> [!NOTE]
> The base case `if (!node) return;` is the first line of nearly every tree function. It quietly handles leaves (their children are `nullptr`) *and* the empty tree, so you almost never need special leaf handling.

Anything phrased by *levels* — "level order", "row by row", "zigzag", "right side view", "average per level" — is a queue, not recursion. The whole template is this, and the load-bearing line is the **size freeze**:

```cpp
// ---------- BFS: level-order with a queue ----------
vector<vector<int>> levelOrder(TreeNode* root) {
    vector<vector<int>> res;
    if (!root) return res;
    queue<TreeNode*> q;
    q.push(root);
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int sz = q.size();               // freeze count: exactly this level
        vector<int> level;
        for (int i = 0; i < sz; ++i) {
            TreeNode* cur = q.front(); q.pop();
            level.push_back(cur->val);
            if (cur->left)  q.push(cur->left);
            if (cur->right) q.push(cur->right);
        }
        res.push_back(move(level));
    }
    return res;
}
```

[[fig:m06-bfs-levels]]

Why the freeze works: when the `while` loop starts an iteration, the queue contains *exactly* the nodes of one level — nothing more, nothing less. Snapshotting `sz` lets you pop exactly those, while their children (the next level) accumulate behind them.

> [!PITFALL]
> Writing `for (int i = 0; i < q.size(); ++i)` instead of freezing `sz` first is the classic bug: every child you push grows `q.size()` mid-loop, so the loop keeps going and **mixes levels together**. Snapshot first, always.

> [!EXAM]
> Most level-flavored OA questions are this exact template plus a one-line tweak: *right side view* = keep the last value of each level; *zigzag* = reverse alternate levels; *level averages* = sum/count per level. Memorize the skeleton so the tweak is the only thinking you do.

deepdives.answer:
**The trap.** The longest path may not pass through the root — and, crucially, a node cannot return "the longest path through me" to its parent. A path that *turns* at a node (goes down-left, then down-right) can't be extended upward: if you returned it, your parent would glue itself onto the middle of a bent path and build something illegal.

> [!KEY] Separate two quantities
> - What you **return** to your parent: the longest *downward* path from this node = `1 + max(L, R)`. This is straight, so it's extendable upward.
> - What you **report** to the global answer: the longest path that *bends* at this node = `L + R` (in edges). Every path in the tree bends at exactly one highest node, so checking `L + R` at every node covers all possible paths.

[[fig:m06-report-return]]

```cpp
int best = 0;
int depth(TreeNode* n) {
    if (!n) return 0;
    int L = depth(n->left), R = depth(n->right);
    best = max(best, L + R);   // REPORT: path bending here (counted in edges)
    return 1 + max(L, R);      // RETURN: one straight arm my parent can extend
}
// answer = best;
```

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time — one visit per node — and $O(h)$ recursion stack.

**What generalizes:** once this clicks, *Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum* is the same skeleton with values instead of edge counts. This report-vs-return idea is the single most reused tree pattern in interviews — narrate it explicitly and you've signaled mastery of the whole family.

**The naive bug (extremely common in interviews):** checking only `node->left->val < node->val < node->right->val` locally. This passes trees that are *not* BSTs — e.g. root 5, right child 6, and 6's left child 3. Every parent-child triple looks fine, but 3 sits in 5's **right** subtree, so it violates the global rule that everything right of 5 must be > 5.

[[fig:m06-bst-bounds]]

> [!KEY] Carry bounds down
> Each node is only valid inside an open interval `(low, high)` inherited from **all** its ancestors, not just its parent. Going left tightens the *upper* bound to the node's value; going right tightens the *lower* bound.

```cpp
bool valid(TreeNode* n, long low, long high) {
    if (!n) return true;
    if (n->val <= low || n->val >= high) return false;
    return valid(n->left,  low, n->val)    // left subtree: max becomes n->val
        && valid(n->right, n->val, high);  // right subtree: min becomes n->val
}
// call: valid(root, LONG_MIN, LONG_MAX);
```

> [!WARNING]
> Use `long` with `LONG_MIN` / `LONG_MAX` for the seeds: node values can be `INT_MIN` or `INT_MAX`, and `int` sentinels would false-fail the comparison at the extremes.

**Alternative:** an inorder traversal of a BST must be *strictly increasing* — track the previous value (or a `TreeNode*` previous pointer, dodging the sentinel issue entirely) and fail if `cur <= prev`.

**Complexity:** both versions are $O(n)$ time, $O(h)$ stack. Explain the bounds version first — it demonstrates you understand *why* the local check is wrong, which is the real question being asked.
